{"title_page": "Colorado Heights University", "text_new": "{{Infobox university|name = Colorado Heights University|image_name =Colorado_Heights_University_Seal.png |caption = |established = 1989|type = Private |officer_in_charge = Fred Van Liew | dean=Tracey Trenam| academic_staff = |administrative_staff = |undergrad = |postgrad = |city = Denver|state = Colorado|country = United States|campus = Urban|former_names = Loretto Heights College, Teikyo Loretto Heights University|colors = Black, Red, Grey, and White {{Color box|black}}{{Color box|red}}{{Color box|grey}}{{Color box|white}}|website = edu.ch.university|students = 400+|coor = {{coord|39.66151|-105.02767|format=dms|display=inline,title|type:edu_region:US-CO}}\n}}\n[[Image:Loretto Heights Academy.JPG|thumb|right|293px|Colorado Heights University]]\n'''Colorado Heights University''' <nowiki>http://edu.ch.university.was</nowiki> an American [[university]] in [[Denver, Colorado]], part of the [[Teikyo University]] Group. In July, 2009 it changed its name from Teikyo Loretto Heights University to Colorado Heights University.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://edu.ch.university/home/news/index.html|title=CHU press releases|last=|first=|date=|website=|publisher=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|accessdate=24 May 2018}}</ref> It opened in 1989 on the campus of the former '''Loretto Heights College'''. Colorado Heights University, shortened to CHU, was a nationally accredited, private university located in Denver, Colorado. More than half of students at CHU came from over 50 different countries.  \n\n==History==\nAt the end of the 19th century, Mother Pancratia (Mary Louise Bonfils 1852-1915),<ref>{{cite web|url=http://blogs.shu.edu/crra/2013/07/17/mother-pancratia-bonfils-1852-1915/|title=Mother Pancratia Bonfils (1852 \u2013 1915) \u2013 Treasures of the Catholic Research Resources Alliance (CRRA)|website=blogs.shu.edu|accessdate=24 May 2018}}</ref> of the [[Sisters of Loretto]], had the vision to educate women in the Rocky Mountain region. In 1886, Loretto Heights Academy was founded as a Catholic girls' high school in the building now used as Colorado Heights University's Administration Building.\n\nThe landmark Administration Building was a Romanesque six-story structure, designed by Denver architect [[Frank E. Edbrooke]] (1840-1921). The Administration Building was built from red sandstone and has been on the National Register of Historic Places since 1975.<ref>[[National Register of Historic Places listings in Denver, Colorado]] - [[National Register of Historic Places listings in West Denver, Colorado]]</ref>\n\nOver the years, the school became a college and expanded to include teacher education programs, nursing programs, business, dance and more for both men and women.<ref>[http://edu.ch.university/home/news/CHU_History.pdf A more detailed history of the CHU campus from its beginning through the 1980s can be found at] </ref> The campus now has almost 20 structures, including a 1,000 seat theater, an interfaith chapel, a swimming pool, cafeteria, residence halls and recreational amenities.\n\nIn 1989, Teikyo Loretto Heights University (TLHU) opened on the campus of the former Loretto Heights College. TLHU focused on international students. In 2009, Colorado Heights University opened. Colorado Heights University was owned by the [[Teikyo University]] Group,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.teikyo-u.ac.jp/english/index.html|title=Teikyo University|website=www.teikyo-u.ac.jp|accessdate=24 May 2018}}</ref> a multinational educational foundation based in Japan that operates many undergraduate and graduate universities with more than 70,000 students spread across 46 campuses world-wide.\n\n==Academics==\nColorado Heights University focused on international business degree programs and English as a Second Language (ESL) courses. It offered Intensive English and [[Test of English as a Foreign Language]] (TOEFL) preparation certificate programs, the Bachelor of Arts in International Business, and various specializations in the Master of Business Administration in International Business.\n\n==Campus==\nIts campus had consisted of 20 buildings on a {{convert|74|acre|m2|adj=on}} site, the highest area in Denver. The Administration Building opened in 1891. Its prominent bell tower could be seen from miles around, serving as a landmark for many Denver residents.\n\n<ref></ref>==Students==\nMost of the students at Colorado Heights University were non-traditional college students. This demographic includes international students, students who speak a language other than English as their native tongue.\n\nMost of the students at Colorado Heights University were bilingual and many are multilingual. It wasn't uncommon to find a student who speaks four or more languages. The primary languages spoken on campus were English, Spanish, Arabic and Russian.\n\nIn addition to the diversity of languages, those students also represented a diversity of cultures, religion and educational backgrounds. In fact, current and past students came to Colorado Heights University from more than 60 countries from Europe, Africa, Asia and the Americas.<ref>List of countries represented at Colorado Heights University: http://edu.ch.university/home/acdemic/catalogue.html</ref>\n[[File:Students with flags.jpg|thumb|]]\n\n<nowiki>==References==</nowiki>\n{{Reflist}}\n\n\n==External links==\n*[http://edu.ch.university/ Official website]\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Sisters of Loretto schools]]\n[[Category:Private universities and colleges in Colorado]]\n[[Category:Universities and colleges in Denver]]\n[[Category:Educational institutions established in 1989]]\n[[Category:Defunct universities and colleges in Colorado]]\n[[Category:1989 establishments in Colorado]]\n[[Category:Educational institutions disestablished in 2017]]\n[[Category:2017 disestablishments in Colorado]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox university|name = Colorado Heights University|image_name =Colorado_Heights_University_Seal.png |caption = |established = 1989|type = Private |officer_in_charge = Fred Van Liew | dean=Tracey Trenam| academic_staff = |administrative_staff = |undergrad = |postgrad = |city = Denver|state = Colorado|country = United States|campus = Urban|former_names = Loretto Heights College, Teikyo Loretto Heights University|colors = Black, Red, Grey, and White {{Color box|black}}{{Color box|red}}{{Color box|grey}}{{Color box|white}}|website = edu.ch.university|students = 400+|coor = {{coord|39.66151|-105.02767|format=dms|display=inline,title|type:edu_region:US-CO}}\n}}\n[[Image:Loretto Heights Academy.JPG|thumb|right|293px|Colorado Heights University]]\n'''Colorado Heights University''' <nowiki>http://edu.ch.university.was</nowiki> an American [[university]] in [[Denver, Colorado]], part of the [[Teikyo University]] Group. In July, 2009 it changed its name from Teikyo Loretto Heights University to Colorado Heights University.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://edu.ch.university/home/news/index.html|title=CHU press releases|last=|first=|date=|website=|publisher=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|accessdate=24 May 2018}}</ref> It opened in 1989 on the campus of the former '''Loretto Heights College'''. Colorado Heights University, shortened to CHU, was a nationally accredited, private university located in Denver, Colorado. More than half of students at CHU came from over 50 different countries.  \n\n==History==\nAt the end of the 19th century, Mother Pancratia (Mary Louise Bonfils 1852-1915),<ref>{{cite web|url=http://blogs.shu.edu/crra/2013/07/17/mother-pancratia-bonfils-1852-1915/|title=Mother Pancratia Bonfils (1852 \u2013 1915) \u2013 Treasures of the Catholic Research Resources Alliance (CRRA)|website=blogs.shu.edu|accessdate=24 May 2018}}</ref> of the [[Sisters of Loretto]], had the vision to educate women in the Rocky Mountain region. In 1886, Loretto Heights Academy was founded as a Catholic girls' high school in the building now used as Colorado Heights University's Administration Building.\n\nThe landmark Administration Building was a Romanesque six-story structure, designed by Denver architect [[Frank E. Edbrooke]] (1840-1921). The Administration Building was built from red sandstone and has been on the National Register of Historic Places since 1975.<ref>[[National Register of Historic Places listings in Denver, Colorado]] - [[National Register of Historic Places listings in West Denver, Colorado]]</ref>\n\nOver the years, the school became a college and expanded to include teacher education programs, nursing programs, business, dance and more for both men and women.<ref>[http://edu.ch.university/home/news/CHU_History.pdf A more detailed history of the CHU campus from its beginning through the 1980s can be found at] </ref> The campus now has almost 20 structures, including a 1,000 seat theater, an interfaith chapel, a swimming pool, cafeteria, residence halls and recreational amenities.\n\nIn 1989, Teikyo Loretto Heights University (TLHU) opened on the campus of the former Loretto Heights College. TLHU focused on international students. In 2009, Colorado Heights University opened. Colorado Heights University was owned by the [[Teikyo University]] Group,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.teikyo-u.ac.jp/english/index.html|title=Teikyo University|website=www.teikyo-u.ac.jp|accessdate=24 May 2018}}</ref> a multinational educational foundation based in Japan that operates many undergraduate and graduate universities with more than 70,000 students spread across 46 campuses world-wide.\n\n==Academics==\nColorado Heights University focused on international business degree programs and English as a Second Language (ESL) courses. It offered Intensive English and [[Test of English as a Foreign Language]] (TOEFL) preparation certificate programs, the Bachelor of Arts in International Business, and various specializations in the Master of Business Administration in International Business.\n\n==Campus==\nIts campus had consisted of 20 buildings on a {{convert|74|acre|m2|adj=on}} site, the highest area in Denver. The Administration Building opened in 1891. Its prominent bell tower could be seen from miles around, serving as a landmark for many Denver residents.\n\n<ref></ref>==Students==\nMost of the students at Colorado Heights University were non-traditional college students. This demographic includes international students, students who speak a language other than English as their native tongue.\n\nMost of the students at Colorado Heights University were bilingual and many are multilingual. It wasn't uncommon to find a student who speaks four or more languages. The primary languages spoken on campus were English, Spanish, Arabic and Russian.\n\nIn addition to the diversity of languages, those students also represented a diversity of cultures, religion and educational backgrounds. In fact, current and past students came to Colorado Heights University from more than 60 countries from Europe, Africa, Asia and the Americas.<ref>List of countries represented at Colorado Heights University: http://edu.ch.university/home/acdemic/catalogue.html</ref>\n[[File:Students with flags.jpg|thumb|]]\n\n[http://edu.ch.university/CHU_History.pdf University history log]==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n\n==External links==\n*[http://edu.ch.university/ Official website]\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Sisters of Loretto schools]]\n[[Category:Private universities and colleges in Colorado]]\n[[Category:Universities and colleges in Denver]]\n[[Category:Educational institutions established in 1989]]\n[[Category:Defunct universities and colleges in Colorado]]\n[[Category:1989 establishments in Colorado]]\n[[Category:Educational institutions disestablished in 2017]]\n[[Category:2017 disestablishments in Colorado]]\n", "name_user": "Universityinf", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eCampus", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Colorado_Heights_University"}
{"title_page": "Ujwal DISCOM Assurance Yojana", "text_new": "{{use dmy dates|date=June 2016}}\n{{use Indian English|date=June 2016}}\n{{Infobox project\n| name = UDAY\n| mission_statement = \"Financial turnaround of Power Distribution Companies\"\n| commercial = Yes\n| location = India\n| owner = Supported by [[Ministry of Power (India)]]\n| founder = [[Centrally Sponsored Scheme ]]\n| established = {{Start date|2015|11}}\n}}\n'''Ujjwal DISCOM Assurance Yojana''' (UDAY) is the financial turnaround and revival package for electricity distribution companies of India (DISCOMs) initiated by the [[Government of India]] with the intent to find a permanent solution to the financial mess that the power distribution is in.<ref>{{cite web|title=UDAY (Ujwal DISCOM Assurance Yojana) for financial turnaround of Power Distribution Companies|url=http://pib.nic.in/newsite/PrintRelease.aspx?relid=130261|website=Press Information Bureau  Government of India Cabinet}}</ref> It allows state governments, which own the DISCOMs, to take over 75 percent of their debt as of September 30, 2015, and pay back lenders by selling bonds.  DISCOMs are expected to issue bonds for the remaining 25 percent of their debt.\n\n== Launch ==\nThe scheme was announced by [[Piyush Goyal]], Minister of State (IC) for Power, Coal & New and Renewable Energy (Now Railway minister and coal minister) in November 2015. The scheme is optional for the states to join. [[Jharkhand]] became the first state to come under uday scheme. Other states that have given their in-principle approval are [[Gujarat]], [[Chhattisgarh]], [[Andhra Pradesh]], [[Karnataka]], [[Rajasthan]], [[Punjab]], [[Haryana]], [[Jammu and Kashmir]], [[Himachal Pradesh]], [[Madhya Pradesh]], [[Uttarakhand]], [[Telangana]], [[Assam]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Telangana to join Centre's Uday scheme today|url=http://www.business-standard.com/article/news-ani/telangana-to-join-centre-s-uday-scheme-today-116062400181_1.html|work=Business Standard India|date=24 June 2016}}</ref>\n\nRecently{{When}} [[Uttar Pradesh]], [[Bihar]], [[Maharashtra]], [[Tamil Nadu]] and [[Mizoram]] joined, thereby making the total of 27 states to have joined.<ref>{{cite news|title=The Uday plug-in|url=http://indianexpress.com/article/opinion/columns/the-uday-plug-in/|work=The Indian Express|date=17 March 2016}}</ref> Till November 2017, only states that have not joined it are [[Odisha]] and [[West Bengal]]. Till now{{When}} 31 states/UT have joined this scheme [[Mizoram]] being the 27th state to join. [[Lakshadweep]] joined the scheme on 28 February, 2018<ref>{{cite web |title=Lakshadweep joins \u201cUDAY\u201d scheme; would derive an overall net benefit of Rs 8 crore through \u201cUDAY\u201d |url=http://pib.nic.in/newsite/PrintRelease.aspx?relid=176895 |website=Press Information Bureau  Government of India}}</ref>, bringing the total of states and Union Territories covered to 32.\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Government Schemes in India}}\n\n[[Category:Electric power in India]]\n[[Category:Modi administration initiatives]]\n[[Category:Government finances in India]]\n[[Category:2015 in Indian economy]]\n", "text_old": "{{use dmy dates|date=June 2016}}\n{{use Indian English|date=June 2016}}\n{{Infobox project\n| name = UDAY\n| mission_statement = \"Financial turnaround of Power Distribution Companies\"\n| commercial = Yes\n| location = India\n| owner = Supported by [[Ministry of Power (India)]]\n| founder = [[Centrally Sponsored Scheme ]]\n| established = {{Start date|2015|11}}\n}}\n'''Ujjwal DISCOM Assurance Yojana''' (UDAY) is the financial turnaround and revival package for electricity distribution companies of India (DISCOMs) initiated by the [[Government of India]] with the intent to find a permanent solution to the financial mess that the power distribution is in.<ref>{{cite web|title=UDAY (Ujwal DISCOM Assurance Yojana) for financial turnaround of Power Distribution Companies|url=http://pib.nic.in/newsite/PrintRelease.aspx?relid=130261|website=Press Information Bureau  Government of India Cabinet}}</ref> It allows state governments, which own the DISCOMs, to take over 75 percent of their debt as of September 30, 2015, and pay back lenders by selling bonds.  DISCOMs are expected to issue bonds for the remaining 25 percent of their debt.\n\n== Launch ==\nThe scheme was announced by [[Piyush Goyal]], Minister of State (IC) for Power, Coal & New and Renewable Energy (Now Railway minister and coal minister) in November 2015. The scheme is optional for the states to join. [[Jharkhand]] became the first state to come under uday scheme. Other states that have given their in-principle approval are [[Gujarat]], [[Chhattisgarh]], [[Andhra Pradesh]], [[Karnataka]], [[Rajasthan]], [[Punjab]], [[Haryana]], [[Jammu and Kashmir]], [[Himachal Pradesh]], [[Madhya Pradesh]], [[Uttarakhand]], [[Telangana]], [[Assam]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Telangana to join Centre's Uday scheme today|url=http://www.business-standard.com/article/news-ani/telangana-to-join-centre-s-uday-scheme-today-116062400181_1.html|work=Business Standard India|date=24 June 2016}}</ref>\n\nRecently{{When}} [[Uttar Pradesh]], [[Bihar]], [[Maharashtra]], [[Tamil Nadu]] and [[Mizoram]] joined, thereby making the total of 27 states to have joined.<ref>{{cite news|title=The Uday plug-in|url=http://indianexpress.com/article/opinion/columns/the-uday-plug-in/|work=The Indian Express|date=17 March 2016}}</ref> Till November 2017, only states that have not joined it are [[Odisha]] and [[West Bengal]]. Till now 31 states/UT have joined this scheme [[Mizoram]] being the 27th state to join. [[Lakshadweep]] joined the scheme on 28 February, 2018<ref>{{cite web |title=Lakshadweep joins \u201cUDAY\u201d scheme; would derive an overall net benefit of Rs 8 crore through \u201cUDAY\u201d |url=http://pib.nic.in/newsite/PrintRelease.aspx?relid=176895 |website=Press Information Bureau  Government of India}}</ref>, bringing the total of states and Union Territories covered to 32.\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Government Schemes in India}}\n\n[[Category:Electric power in India]]\n[[Category:Modi administration initiatives]]\n[[Category:Government finances in India]]\n[[Category:2015 in Indian economy]]\n", "name_user": "Zingzingerat", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eLaunch", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ujwal_DISCOM_Assurance_Yojana"}
{"title_page": "Wi (kana)", "text_new": "{{Unreferenced|date=December 2009}}\n{{Infobox kana\n| Hiragana image = Japanese Hiragana kyokashotai WI.png\n| Katakana image = Japanese Katakana WI.png\n| Transliteration = i, wi\n| Hiragana Manyogana = \u7232\n| Katakana Manyogana = \u4e95\n| Braille = [[File:Japanese Wi Braille.svg|32px|\u2806]]\n| Unicode = U+3090, U+30F0\n| flag1 = 6\n| flag2 = 12\n| Footnotes =\n|Spelling=\u3090\u3069\u306e\u30f0 [[well|(W)ido]] no \"(w)i\"\n}}\n{{kana gojuon sidebar}}\n\n'''\u3090''', in [[hiragana]], or '''\u30f0''' in [[katakana]], is a nearly obsolete Japanese [[kana]], each of which represent one [[Mora (linguistics)|mora]]. It is presumed that \u3090 represented {{IPA-ja|\u0270i||Ja-Wi.oga}} and that \u3090 and \u3044 indicated different pronunciations  until somewhere between the [[Kamakura period]] and the [[Taish\u014d period]] when they both came to be pronounced {{IPA|[i]}}. Along with the kana for [[We (kana)|we]] (\u3091 in hiragana, \u30f1 in katakana), this kana was deemed obsolete in Japanese in 1946, and replaced with [[I (kana)|\u3044 and \u30a4]]. It is now rare in everyday usage; in [[onomatopoeia]] and foreign words, the katakana form \u30a6\u30a3 (U-[small-i]) is preferred.\n\nThe kana still sees some modern-day usage. The spelling of [[whisky]] is usually \"\u30a6\u30a4\u30b9\u30ad\u30fc\" (uisuk\u012b), but sometimes written \"\u30a6\u30f0\u30b9\u30ad\u30fc\" (uwisuk\u012b) stylistically, such as {{nihongo|[[Nikka Whisky Distilling|Nikka Whisky]]|\u30cb\u30c3\u30ab\u30a6\u30f0\u30b9\u30ad\u30fc|nikka uwisuk\u012b}}. The name of the comedy duo [[Yoiko]] is written \"\u3088\u3090\u3053\" (yowiko), a character in the video game series ''[[Touhou Project]]'' has the name \"\u3066\u3090\" (Tewi) and the first opening theme to the [[Future Diary]] anime series is entitled \"\u7a7a\u60f3\u30e1\u30bd\u30ed\u30ae\u30f0\" (Kuusou Mesorogiwi).  Katakana \u30f0 is sometimes written with a dakuten, \u30f8, to represent a {{IPA|/vi/}} sound in foreign words; however, most [[Input method|IME]]s lack a convenient way to do this.  It is far more common for /vi/ to be represented by the combination \u30f4\u30a3.\n\nHiragana \u3090 is still used in one of the [[Okinawan writing system|Okinawan orthographies]], New Okinawan, for the syllable {{IPA|/wi/}} and in digraphs for {{IPA|/kwi, \u0261wi/}}. In the Ryukyu University system, katakana \u30f0 is used for {{IPA|/i/}}, while \u3044 is {{IPA|/\u0294i/}}. Katakana \u30f0 is also used in [[Ainu language#Writing|Ainu]] for {{IPA|/wi/}}.\n\n==History==\n\n===Nara period (710 \u2013 794 AD)===\nDuring the [[Nara period]], \u30f0 was pronounced as [wi] and \u30a4  as [i].  In the [[Man'y\u014dgana]], there were characters to represent \u30f0 (e.g. \u4e95, \u4f4d, \u7232, \u732a, \u8b02, \u85cd) and \u30a4 (e.g. \u5df2, \u4e94, \u4ee5, \u4f0a, \u6021, \u5c04, \u79fb, \u7570); no characters for one could be used to pronounce the other.  The labial glides \u30af{{small|\u30f0}} [k\u02b7i] and \u30b0{{small|\u30f0}} [g\u02b7i] also existed (though in those days small script kana were not used for glides), and were distinct from \u30ad [ki] and \u30ae [gi].\n\n===Heian Period (794 \u2013 1184 AD)===\nDuring the [[Heian period]], \u3090 and \u3044 were still recognized as separately pronounced characters.  In the mid-to-late 11th century, the [[Iroha]] song was developed, and \u3044, \u3048, and \u304a (''i'', ''e'', and ''o'') were differentiated from \u3090, \u3091, and \u3092 (''wi'', ''we'', and ''wo'').  In the [[Goj\u016bon]] ordering (developed around 1075 by the scholar Hirotomo, based on the [[Siddha\u1e43 script]]), there were no sounds for \u201cyi\u201d, \u201cye\u201d, \u201cwu\u201d, or \u201cwo\u201d.  Although the distinction had been lost between \u30aa (''o'') and \u30f2 (''wo''), there was still a distinction between  \u30a2/\u30ef (''a/wa''), \u30a4/\u30f0 (''i/wi''), and \u30a8/\u30f1 (''e/we'').\n\nIn Ki no Tsurayuki\u2019s literary work, the [[Tosa Nikki]] (originally written in 935, transcribed in 1236), the phrase \u201c\u6d77\u8cca\u5831\u3044\u305b\u3080\u201d (''kaizoku mukui semu'') is written as \u201c\u304b\u3044\u305e\u304f\u3080\u304f'''\u3090'''\u305b\u3080\u201d (''kaizoku muku'''wi''' semu''), with \u3090 where \u3044 should be.  In this way, examples of confusion between \u3090 and \u3044 were emerging, little by little; however, during the Heian period these confusions were few and far between.\n\nSince the Nara period, /h/ began to be pronounced as [w] in word-medial position; by the beginning of the 11th century, this phenomenon, called the \"Ha-line shift\", had become more widespread.  In word-medial or word-final position, \u3072 [\u0278i] would be pronounced [wi], therefore becoming the same as \u3090.  Because of this, the use of \u3072 and \u3090 also became confused.\n\nAt the end of the 12th century, the literary work \u201cShinky\u014d Shiki Ch\u016b\u201d (which contained [[katakana]], from the last years of the [[Cloistered rule|Insei period]]) attests examples of \u3090 and \u3044 losing their distinction, such as \u201c\u7387\u3066\u201d (''wite'') being written \u201c\u30a4\u30c6\u201d (''ite'').\n\nFurthermore, in Heian period literature, special kanji readings such as \u201c\u30af\u30f0\u30e4\u30a6\u201d [k\u02b7\u02b2au] and \u201c\u30f0\u30e4\u30a6\u201d [w\u02b2au] were used, but were not well established.\n\n===Kamakura Period (1185\u20131333 AD)===\nBy the [[Kamakura period]], the confusion between \u3090 and \u3044 had become even more widespread, and by the 13th century, \u3090 and \u3044 were unified.  By changing from [wi] to [i], \u3090 had merged into \u3044.  Also, kanji that were represented by \u30af\u30f0 and \u30b0\u30f0 had become pronounced [ki] and [gi] respectively, merging them with \u30ad and \u30ae.\n\nDue to the Ha-line shift as well as the merging of a number of syllables, soon there were many kana pronounced the same way, and kana orthography was in chaos.  [[Fujiwara no Teika]] (1162\u20131241), in the \u201cUnpleasant Characters\u201d section of Gekansh\u016b (a poetry volume), established rules for about 60 words containing \u3092/\u304a, \u3048/\u3078/\u3091, and \u3044/\u3072/\u3090, based on a number of writings from the mid-11th to 12th century.  However, the books that Teika had referenced already contained a number of confusions, with \u3072 becoming \u3090, such as \u9042 (formerly \u201c\u3064\u3072\u201d ''tsuhi'') being represented as \u201c\u3064\u3090\u201d (''tsuwi'') and \u5bb5 (formerly \u201c\u3088\u3072\u201d ''yohi'') being represented as \u201c\u3088\u3090\u201d (''yowi''); \u3044 becoming either \u3072 or \u3090, such as \u8001\u3044 (historically \u201c\u304a\u3044\u201d ''oi'') being represented as \u201c\u304a\u3090\u201d (''owi'') or \u201c\u304a\u3072\u201d (''ohi''); and various other spellings differing from their original pronunciation.  Teika\u2019s syllabary particularly drew from poetry such as [[Waka (poetry)|''waka'']] and ''[[renga]]'', but a number of examples of confusion between \u3044, \u3090, and word-medial/final \u3072 were also frequently pulled from other sources.\n\n===Muromachi Period (1333\u20131573 AD)===\nIn the [[Nanboku-ch\u014d period]], the scholar Gy\u014da published the ''Kanamojizukai'' (Kana Character Syllabary, completed in 1363), drastically augmenting the lexicon by over 1000 words.  Though the ''Kanamojizukai'' was generally as widely accepted as Teika\u2019s syllabary, in practice there were a number of kana pronunciations that did not conform to it.\n\nIn Christian [[r\u014dmaji]] documents from the 16th century (the later part of the [[Muromachi period]]), \u3090 and \u3044 were written with either \u201ci\u201d, \u201cj\u201d, or \u201cy\u201d, but the pronunciation was understood to be [i] in any case.\n\nNot to be confused with [[\u3044]](i).\n\n==Stroke order==\n{|\n|+\n|-\n| [[File:Hiragana \u3090 stroke order animation.gif|thumb|downright|alt=Stroke order in writing \u3090|Stroke order in writing \u3090]]\n| [[File:Katakana \u30f0 stroke order animation.gif|thumb|upright|tlr=Stroke order in writing \u30f0|Stroke order in writing \u30f0]]\n|}\n\n[[Image:\u3090-bw.png|200px|right|Stroke order in writing \u3090]]\nThe Hiragana \u3090 is made with one [[Stroke (Chinese character)|stroke]]. It resembles the second stroke of the Hiragana [[nu (kana)|\u306c]], with an additional short horizontal line at the start.\n\n[[Image:\u30f0-bw.png|200px|right|Stroke order in writing \u30f0]]\nThe Katakana \u30f0 is made with four [[Stroke (Chinese character)|strokes]]:\n# A horizontal line.\n# A vertical line.\n# A horizontal line.\n# A vertical line.\n\n==Other representations==\n* [[Character encoding|Computer encodings]]\n{{charmap\n|3090|name1=Hiragana Letter Wi\n|30F0|name2=Katakana Letter Wi\n|map1=[[Shift JIS]]|map1char1=82 EE|map1char2=83 90\n}}\n\n* Braille\n{| class=\"wikitable nowrap\" style=\"text-align:center\"\n|- \n!colspan=4| \u3090 / \u30f0 in [[Japanese Braille]]\n|-\n| \u3090 / \u30f0 <br />'''wi''' || \u30f8 <br />'''vi''' || \u3090\u3044 / \u30f0\u30fc <br />'''w\u012b''' || \u30f8\u30fc <br />'''v\u012b''' \n|-\n| {{Braille cell|type=kana|size=30px|\u3090}}\u3000\n| {{Braille cell|type=kana|size=30px|5|\u3090}}\n| {{Braille cell|type=kana|size=30px|\u3090|25}}\n| {{Braille cell|type=kana|size=30px|5|\u3090|25}}\n|}\n\n* [[Japanese semaphore]]\n[[File:Japanese Semaphore Basic Stroke 6.svg|50px]]\n[[File:Japanese Semaphore Basic Stroke 12.svg|50px]]\n\n==See also==\n*[[U (kana)]]\n*[[I (kana)]]\n\n{{Wiktionary|\u3090|\u30f0}}\n{{Commonscat|\u3090}}\n{{Commonscat|\u30f0}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Wi (Kana)}}\n[[Category:Specific kana]]\n", "text_old": "{{Unreferenced|date=December 2009}}\n{{Infobox kana\n| Hiragana image = Japanese Hiragana kyokashotai WI.png\n| Katakana image = Japanese Katakana WI.png\n| Transliteration = i, wi\n| Hiragana Manyogana = \u7232\n| Katakana Manyogana = \u4e95\n| Braille = [[File:Japanese Wi Braille.svg|32px|\u2806]]\n| Unicode = U+3090, U+30F0\n| flag1 = 6\n| flag2 = 12\n| Footnotes =\n|Spelling=\u3090\u3069\u306e\u30f0 [[well|(W)ido]] no \"(w)i\"\n}}\n{{kana gojuon sidebar}}\n\n'''\u3090''', in [[hiragana]], or '''\u30f0''' in [[katakana]], is a nearly obsolete Japanese [[kana]], each of which represent one [[Mora (linguistics)|mora]]. It is presumed that \u3090 represented {{IPA-ja|\u0270i||Ja-Wi.oga}} and that \u3090 and \u3044 indicated different pronunciations  until somewhere between the [[Kamakura period]] and the [[Taish\u014d period]] when they both came to be pronounced {{IPA|[i]}}. Along with the kana for [[We (kana)|we]] (\u3091 in hiragana, \u30f1 in katakana), this kana was deemed obsolete in Japanese in 1946, and replaced with [[I (kana)|\u3044 and \u30a4]]. It is now rare in everyday usage; in [[onomatopoeia]] and foreign words, the katakana form \u30a6\u30a3 (U-[small-i]) is preferred.\n\nThe kana still sees some modern-day usage. The spelling of [[whisky]] is usually \"\u30a6\u30a4\u30b9\u30ad\u30fc\" (uisuk\u012b), but sometimes written \"\u30a6\u30f0\u30b9\u30ad\u30fc\" (uwisuk\u012b) stylistically, such as {{nihongo|[[Nikka Whisky Distilling|Nikka Whisky]]|\u30cb\u30c3\u30ab\u30a6\u30f0\u30b9\u30ad\u30fc|nikka uwisuk\u012b}}. The name of the comedy duo [[Yoiko]] is written \"\u3088\u3090\u3053\" (yowiko), a character in the video game series ''[[Touhou Project]]'' has the name \"\u3066\u3090\" (Tewi) and the first opening theme to the [[Future Diary]] anime series is entitled \"\u7a7a\u60f3\u30e1\u30bd\u30ed\u30ae\u30f0\" (Kuusou Mesorogiwi).  Katakana \u30f0 is sometimes written with a dakuten, \u30f8, to represent a {{IPA|/vi/}} sound in foreign words; however, most [[Input method|IME]]s lack a convenient way to do this.  It is far more common for /vi/ to be represented by the combination \u30f4\u30a3.\n\nHiragana \u3090 is still used in one of the [[Okinawan writing system|Okinawan orthographies]], New Okinawan, for the syllable {{IPA|/wi/}} and in digraphs for {{IPA|/kwi, \u0261wi/}}. In the Ryukyu University system, katakana \u30f0 is used for {{IPA|/i/}}, while \u3044 is {{IPA|/\u0294i/}}. Katakana \u30f0 is also used in [[Ainu language#Writing|Ainu]] for {{IPA|/wi/}}.\n\n==History==\n\n===Nara period (710 \u2013 794 AD)===\nDuring the [[Nara period]], \u30f0 was pronounced as [wi] and \u30a4  as [i].  In the [[Man'y\u014dgana]], there were characters to represent \u30f0 (e.g. \u4e95, \u4f4d, \u7232, \u732a, \u8b02, \u85cd) and \u30a4 (e.g. \u5df2, \u4e94, \u4ee5, \u4f0a, \u6021, \u5c04, \u79fb, \u7570); no characters for one could be used to pronounce the other.  The labial glides \u30af{{small|\u30f0}} [k\u02b7i] and \u30b0{{small|\u30f0}} [g\u02b7i] also existed (though in those days small script kana were not used for glides), and were distinct from \u30ad [ki] and \u30ae [gi].\n\n===Heian Period (794 \u2013 1184 AD)===\nDuring the [[Heian period]], \u3090 and \u3044 were still recognized as separately pronounced characters.  In the mid-to-late 11th century, the [[Iroha]] song was developed, and \u3044, \u3048, and \u304a (''i'', ''e'', and ''o'') were differentiated from \u3090, \u3091, and \u3092 (''wi'', ''we'', and ''wo'').  In the [[Goj\u016bon]] ordering (developed around 1075 by the scholar Hirotomo, based on the [[Siddha\u1e43 script]]), there were no sounds for \u201cyi\u201d, \u201cye\u201d, \u201cwu\u201d, or \u201cwo\u201d.  Although the distinction had been lost between \u30aa (''o'') and \u30f2 (''wo''), there was still a distinction between  \u30a2/\u30ef (''a/wa''), \u30a4/\u30f0 (''i/wi''), and \u30a8/\u30f1 (''e/we'').\n\nIn Ki no Tsurayuki\u2019s literary work, the [[Tosa Nikki]] (originally written in 935, transcribed in 1236), the phrase \u201c\u6d77\u8cca\u5831\u3044\u305b\u3080\u201d (''kaizoku mukui semu'') is written as \u201c\u304b\u3044\u305e\u304f\u3080\u304f'''\u3090'''\u305b\u3080\u201d (''kaizoku muku'''wi''' semu''), with \u3090 where \u3044 should be.  In this way, examples of confusion between \u3090 and \u3044 were emerging, little by little; however, during the Heian period these confusions were few and far between.\n\nSince the Nara period, /h/ began to be pronounced as [w] in word-medial position; by the beginning of the 11th century, this phenomenon, called the \"Ha-line shift\", had become more widespread.  In word-medial or word-final position, \u3072 [\u0278i] would be pronounced [wi], therefore becoming the same as \u3090.  Because of this, the use of \u3072 and \u3090 also became confused.\n\nAt the end of the 12th century, the literary work \u201cShinky\u014d Shiki Ch\u016b\u201d (which contained [[katakana]], from the last years of the [[Cloistered rule|Insei period]]) attests examples of \u3090 and \u3044 losing their distinction, such as \u201c\u7387\u3066\u201d (''wite'') being written \u201c\u30a4\u30c6\u201d (''ite'').\n\nFurthermore, in Heian period literature, special kanji readings such as \u201c\u30af\u30f0\u30e4\u30a6\u201d [k\u02b7\u02b2au] and \u201c\u30f0\u30e4\u30a6\u201d [w\u02b2au] were used, but were not well established.\n\n===Kamakura Period (1185\u20131333 AD)===\nBy the [[Kamakura period]], the confusion between \u3090 and \u3044 had become even more widespread, and by the 13th century, \u3090 and \u3044 were unified.  By changing from [wi] to [i], \u3090 had merged into \u3044.  Also, kanji that were represented by \u30af\u30f0 and \u30b0\u30f0 had become pronounced [ki] and [gi] respectively, merging them with \u30ad and \u30ae.\n\nDue to the Ha-line shift as well as the merging of a number of syllables, soon there were many kana pronounced the same way, and kana orthography was in chaos.  [[Fujiwara no Teika]] (1162\u20131241), in the \u201cUnpleasant Characters\u201d section of Gekansh\u016b (a poetry volume), established rules for about 60 words containing \u3092/\u304a, \u3048/\u3078/\u3091, and \u3044/\u3072/\u3090, based on a number of writings from the mid-11th to 12th century.  However, the books that Teika had referenced already contained a number of confusions, with \u3072 becoming \u3090, such as \u9042 (formerly \u201c\u3064\u3072\u201d ''tsuhi'') being represented as \u201c\u3064\u3090\u201d (''tsuwi'') and \u5bb5 (formerly \u201c\u3088\u3072\u201d ''yohi'') being represented as \u201c\u3088\u3090\u201d (''yowi''); \u3044 becoming either \u3072 or \u3090, such as \u8001\u3044 (historically \u201c\u304a\u3044\u201d ''oi'') being represented as \u201c\u304a\u3090\u201d (''owi'') or \u201c\u304a\u3072\u201d (''ohi''); and various other spellings differing from their original pronunciation.  Teika\u2019s syllabary particularly drew from poetry such as [[Waka (poetry)|''waka'']] and ''[[renga]]'', but a number of examples of confusion between \u3044, \u3090, and word-medial/final \u3072 were also frequently pulled from other sources.\n\n===Muromachi Period (1333\u20131573 AD)===\nIn the [[Nanboku-ch\u014d period]], the scholar Gy\u014da published the ''Kanamojizukai'' (Kana Character Syllabary, completed in 1363), drastically augmenting the lexicon by over 1000 words.  Though the ''Kanamojizukai'' was generally as widely accepted as Teika\u2019s syllabary, in practice there were a number of kana pronunciations that did not conform to it.\n\nIn Christian [[r\u014dmaji]] documents from the 16th century (the later part of the [[Muromachi period]]), \u3090 and \u3044 were written with either \u201ci\u201d, \u201cj\u201d, or \u201cy\u201d, but the pronunciation was understood to be [i] in any case.\n\n==Stroke order==\n{|\n|+\n|-\n| [[File:Hiragana \u3090 stroke order animation.gif|thumb|downright|alt=Stroke order in writing \u3090|Stroke order in writing \u3090]]\n| [[File:Katakana \u30f0 stroke order animation.gif|thumb|upright|tlr=Stroke order in writing \u30f0|Stroke order in writing \u30f0]]\n|}\n\n[[Image:\u3090-bw.png|200px|right|Stroke order in writing \u3090]]\nThe Hiragana \u3090 is made with one [[Stroke (Chinese character)|stroke]]. It resembles the second stroke of the Hiragana [[nu (kana)|\u306c]], with an additional short horizontal line at the start.\n\n[[Image:\u30f0-bw.png|200px|right|Stroke order in writing \u30f0]]\nThe Katakana \u30f0 is made with four [[Stroke (Chinese character)|strokes]]:\n# A horizontal line.\n# A vertical line.\n# A horizontal line.\n# A vertical line.\n\n==Other representations==\n* [[Character encoding|Computer encodings]]\n{{charmap\n|3090|name1=Hiragana Letter Wi\n|30F0|name2=Katakana Letter Wi\n|map1=[[Shift JIS]]|map1char1=82 EE|map1char2=83 90\n}}\n\n* Braille\n{| class=\"wikitable nowrap\" style=\"text-align:center\"\n|- \n!colspan=4| \u3090 / \u30f0 in [[Japanese Braille]]\n|-\n| \u3090 / \u30f0 <br />'''wi''' || \u30f8 <br />'''vi''' || \u3090\u3044 / \u30f0\u30fc <br />'''w\u012b''' || \u30f8\u30fc <br />'''v\u012b''' \n|-\n| {{Braille cell|type=kana|size=30px|\u3090}}\u3000\n| {{Braille cell|type=kana|size=30px|5|\u3090}}\n| {{Braille cell|type=kana|size=30px|\u3090|25}}\n| {{Braille cell|type=kana|size=30px|5|\u3090|25}}\n|}\n\n* [[Japanese semaphore]]\n[[File:Japanese Semaphore Basic Stroke 6.svg|50px]]\n[[File:Japanese Semaphore Basic Stroke 12.svg|50px]]\n\n==See also==\n*[[U (kana)]]\n*[[I (kana)]]\n\n{{Wiktionary|\u3090|\u30f0}}\n{{Commonscat|\u3090}}\n{{Commonscat|\u30f0}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Wi (Kana)}}\n[[Category:Specific kana]]\n", "name_user": "188.163.99.108", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "(\u2192\u200eHistory)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wi_(kana)"}
{"title_page": "Waterfront Streetcar", "text_new": "{{short description|Former heritage streetcar line in Seattle, Washington}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=January 2016}}\n{{Infobox rail line\n| name        = Waterfront Streetcar\n| color       = 002C59\n| logo        =\n| logo_width  =\n| image       = SeaWaterfrontStreetcar OccidentalPark.jpg\n| image_width =\n| caption     = Car 272 eastbound on Main Street,<br /> at the Occidental Park stop\n| type        = [[Heritage streetcar|Heritage]] [[Tram|streetcar]]\n| system      =\n| status      = Discontinued\n| locale      = [[Seattle, Washington|Seattle]]\n| start       = Broad Street at Alaskan Way\n| end         = Jackson Street at 5th Avenue\n| stations    = 9\n| routes      = 1\n| daily_ridership =\n| open        = May 29, 1982\n| close       = November 18, 2005\n| owner       =\n| operator    = [[King County Metro]]\n| character   = [[At-grade]]\n| depot       =\n| stock       = 5 [[W-class Melbourne tram|Melbourne W2 trams]]\n| linelength  = {{convert|1.6|mi|km|2|abbr=on}}\n| tracklength =\n| tracks      = \n| gauge       = {{RailGauge|ussg|allk=on}}\n| minradius   =\n| electrification = [[Overhead lines|Overhead wires]], 600 [[Volt|V]] [[Direct current|DC]]\n| speed       =\n| map         = {{Seattle Waterfront Streetcar|inline=1}}\n| map_state   =\n}}\n\nThe '''Waterfront Streetcar''', officially the '''George Benson Waterfront Streetcar Line''', was a [[heritage streetcar|heritage]] [[tram|streetcar line]] run by [[King County Metro]] in [[Seattle]], Washington, United States. It traveled for {{convert|1.6|mi|km|adj=on}} along [[Alaskan Way]] on the city's waterfront facing [[Elliott Bay]], under the [[Alaskan Way Viaduct]]. The Waterfront Streetcar used a fleet of five [[W-class Melbourne tram|W2 trams]] from [[Melbourne]], Australia.\n\nService began on May 29, 1982, the first streetcars to run in Seattle since the closure of the [[Seattle Municipal Street Railway]] on April 13, 1941. It initially terminated at [[Occidental Park (Seattle)|Occidental Park]] in [[Pioneer Square, Seattle|Pioneer Square]] until the line was extended to [[International District/Chinatown station]] in 1990. Service was officially suspended on November 18, 2005, when the maintenance barn and Broad Street station were demolished to make room for the [[Seattle Art Museum]]'s [[Olympic Sculpture Park]]. A large portion of the trackage and four stations were demolished in 2012 as part of the reconstruction of Alaskan Way.\n\nStreetcar service was replaced by King County Metro Route 99, which operated along Alaskan Way until February 2011 when construction forced Metro to reroute the line to 1st Avenue. King County Metro announced in January 2016 that a private venture would launch a fundraising effort to retrofit two of the historic Waterfront Streetcar vehicles to run alongside modern [[Seattle Streetcar]] vehicles on the [[Seattle Streetcar#Center City Connector|Center City Connector]] along 1st Avenue.\n\n==History==\n\nThe original [[Seattle Municipal Street Railway|city streetcar system]] in Seattle ceased operations in April 1941 and was replaced with a network of [[Trolleybuses in Seattle|electric trolleybuses]] and motor buses. City councilman [[George Benson (American politician)|George Benson]] (1919\u20132004) first proposed the idea of building a streetcar line along the Seattle waterfront in 1974, a year after he was elected to the council, to be operational in time for the national [[United States Bicentennial|Bicentennial]] on July 4, 1976.<ref name=\"times-1982may30\">{{cite news |last=Emery |first=Julie |title=Streetcar desire turns to real thing on waterfront |newspaper=The Seattle Times |date=May 30, 1982 |page=B1}}</ref><ref name=\"MT-1982Jan\">{{cite news |last=Price |first=J.H. |title=Museum News |magazine=[[Modern Tramway]] |publisher=[[Ian Allan Publishing]] |date=January 1982 |location=UK |page=30}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=Lane |first=Bob |date=August 20, 1974 |title=Firm will study streetcar plan |page=B8 |work=The Seattle Times}}</ref> The line would use vintage streetcars, and the goal was to create an attraction that would bring tourists and local residents to the waterfront, to help rejuvenate the area, which had already begun a slow transition from a purely industrial district to one with shops and cultural attractions such as the (then-planned, later built) [[Seattle Aquarium]]. Eventually, the proposal garnered enough support from the public and Benson's fellow council members that funds were allocated for an engineering and design study,<ref name=\"MT-1982Jan\"/> ultimately leading to the approval of the project.\n\nThe line used previously existing freight railroad tracks adjacent to [[Alaskan Way]], and construction for the streetcar project involved adding [[trolley wires|overhead trolley wires]], high-platform stations, and a [[passing loop|passing track]] near the middle of the line, which otherwise was [[Single-track railway|single-track]].<ref name=\"MT-1982Jan\"/>  The line started just north of Broad Street, near Pier 70, and until 1990 ran only as far south as Main Street, terminating at a station next to Alaskan Way, immediately south of Main.<ref name=\"MT-1982Jan\"/>\n\nService began on May 29, 1982,<ref name=\"times-1982may30\"/> which was the first streetcar run in Seattle since April 13, 1941. The first three streetcars had been brought to Seattle from [[Melbourne]], Australia, by Councilman Benson in 1978. They had been [[Melbourne and Metropolitan Tramways Board]] cars 482, 512 and 518, and they kept those numbers in Seattle. Two more Melbourne streetcars were acquired between 1990 and 1993. All were [[W-class Melbourne tram|W2-class]] trams that had originally been built between 1925 and 1930.\n\nIn 1989, construction began on a quarter-mile extension of the streetcar along Main Street and 5th Avenue to Jackson Street, to connect to the [[International District/Chinatown (Link station)|International District/Chinatown Station]] of the then-new [[Downtown Seattle Transit Tunnel]].<ref name=\"idea to reality\">{{cite news |last=Benson |first=George |url=http://www.historylink.org/index.cfm?DisplayPage=output.cfm&file_id=7271 |year=1992 |publisher=[[HistoryLink.org]] |title=The Seattle Waterfront Streetcar -- The Steep Grade from Idea to Reality by George Benson |accessdate=June 8, 2009}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=Carter |first=Don |date=July 26, 1989 |title=Ground broken for extension of the waterfront's streetcar line |page=B1 |work=Seattle Post-Intelligencer}}</ref> The extension opened for regular service on June 23, 1990.<ref name=\"idea to reality\"/><ref name=mt-sep90>''[[Tramways & Urban Transit|Modern Tramway]]'', September 1990, p. 321. [[Ian Allan Publishing]]/[[Light Rail Transit Association]] (UK).</ref> The line's fourth ex-Melbourne streetcar, No. 272, entered service earlier that month.<ref name=mt-sep90/> A fifth car of the same type, No. 605, entered service on June 1, 1993.<ref name=\"LRMT-1993Sep\">{{cite news |title=World News [regular news section] |magazine=[[Light Rail & Modern Tramway]] |publisher=[[Ian Allan Publishing]] |date=September 1993 |location=UK |page=249}}</ref> On June 1, 2020, the King County Council approved legislation to rename the line in honor of councilmember Benson, christening it the \"George Benson Waterfront Streetcar Line\". The streetcar stations were rebranded and repainted in August 2003.<ref>{{cite press release |date=August 11, 2003 |title=Metro goes retro with streetcar stations |url=http://transit.metrokc.gov/up/archives/2003/8-11wscstations.html |publisher=King County Metro |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090814092357/http://transit.metrokc.gov/up/archives/2003/8-11wscstations.html |archivedate=August 14, 2009 |accessdate=March 10, 2020}}</ref>\n\n===Cancellation of service===\n\n[[File:Seattle streetcar at Broad Street Station.jpg|thumb|left|Broad Street station]]\nThe streetcar ceased operation on November 18, 2005, when the maintenance barn was demolished to make room for the [[Seattle Art Museum]]'s [[Olympic Sculpture Park]].<ref name=\"lastday\">{{cite news |date=November 19, 2005 |title=Waterfront trolley's last lullaby until 2007 |work=[[Seattle Post-Intelligencer]] |url=http://www.seattlepi.com/transportation/249090_streetcar19.html |accessdate=May 3, 2010}}{{dead link|date=August 2011}}</ref> A new maintenance barn was proposed to be built at Occidental Park to allow the resumption of operations as early as summer 2007.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://community.seattletimes.nwsource.com/archive/?date=20060629&slug=trolleybarn29m |title=Trolley-maintenance barn plan on hold; streetcar future unclear |work=The Seattle Times |date=June 29, 2006 |accessdate=August 6, 2011}}</ref> However, [[King County Metro|Metro]] cancelled involvement after delays made the new facility unlikely to be completed before the demolition of the [[Alaskan Way Viaduct]] began.<ref name=sea-times-2008apr>{{cite news |last=Eskenazi |first=Stuart |url=http://seattletimes.nwsource.com/html/localnews/2004341603_streetcar11m.html |date=April 11, 2008 |newspaper=[[The Seattle Times]] |title=Waterfront streetcar: Is it gone for good? |accessdate=June 8, 2009}}</ref> An alternative proposal by the [[Port of Seattle]] was to extend the line northward along [[Myrtle Edwards Park]] to [[Smith Cove (Washington)|Smith Cove]], where a new maintenance barn would be built on Port property.<ref>{{cite news |last=Hadley |first=Jane |url=http://www.seattlepi.com/transportation/217355_samtrolley24.html |date=March 24, 2005 |newspaper=[[Seattle Post-Intelligencer]] |title=Port plan would extend and save waterfront trolley |accessdate=December 14, 2009}}</ref> This proposal was not pursued.\n\nIn 2007, two years into the suspension of service, the route was named by National Geographic Society as one of the 10 Great Streetcar routes.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.thestar.com/News/GTA/article/289399 |first=Christopher |last=Hume |author2=Kalinowski, Tess |newspaper=[[Toronto Star]] |date=December 29, 2007 |title=Toronto streetcar named among world's best |accessdate=July 24, 2008}}</ref>\n\nIn spring 2012, a large portion of the trackage and the stations at Pike, University, Madison and Washington streets were demolished in as a part of the construction project drilling a [[Alaskan Way Viaduct replacement tunnel|deep bore tunnel]] to replace the Alaskan Way Viaduct.\n\nThe City of Seattle began studying the possibility of bringing streetcars back to the city center in late 2012. The locally preferred alternative for this project adopted in late 2014 supported a route along 1st Avenue and not Alaskan Way. James Corner Field Operations, the Manhattan-based landscape-architecture firm hired to recommend a new vision for the Seattle waterfront once the Viaduct has been demolished, also recommended the Streetcar not be returned to Alaskan Way, but to nearby First Avenue instead.\n\nWhile future plans for the line were determined, the streetcars were stored in an old warehouse in SoDo for more than a decade. In 2015, the Federal Transit Administration informed King County that if the streetcars are not put back in service soon, Metro would need to pay $205,000 to compensate the agency for its remaining investment in the cars.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web |url=http://saveourstreetcar.org/seattles-old-waterfront-streetcars-will-live-on-in-different-ways/ |title=Seattle's old waterfront streetcars will live on \u2013 in different ways [excerpt from KING 5 News story] |date=January 14, 2016|access-date = August 10, 2016 |website=Saveourstreetcar.org |publisher=Friends of the Benson Trolleys |last= |first=}}</ref> At the same time, the warehouse used to store the streetcars was in poor condition and the land needed for expansion of a neighboring bus base.<ref name=\":1\" />\n\n[[File:Ex-Melbourne tram 482 loaded onto truck trailer in Seattle for its move to St Louis, June 2016.jpg|thumb|left|Car 482 loaded onto a truck trailer, about to leave for St. Louis]]\n\nIn January 2016, it was announced that a private venture, Friends of the Benson Trolleys, was intending to raise the money required to retrofit two of the streetcars to allow them to be used on the future [[Seattle Streetcar#Future lines|Center City Connector]] on 1st Avenue.<ref name=\"king-2016jan\">{{cite news |last=Green |first=Josh |date=January 14, 2016 |title=Seattle's old waterfront streetcars will live on - in different ways |url=http://www.king5.com/story/news/local/seattle/2016/01/14/seattles-old-waterfront-streetcars-live---different-ways/78825108/ |publisher=[[KING-TV]] |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160125062226/http://www.king5.com/story/news/local/seattle/2016/01/14/seattles-old-waterfront-streetcars-live---different-ways/78825108/ |archivedate=January 25, 2016 |accessdate=January 14, 2016}}</ref> The plan closely mirrors one suggested in May 2009 by then Seattle Mayor, [[Greg Nickels]].<ref name=\"Seattle Post Globe\">{{cite news |last=Murakami |first=Kery |url=http://seattlepostglobe.org/2009/05/16/tracking-down-seattles-missing-vintage-streetcars |date=May 16, 2009 |publisher=[[Seattle PostGlobe]] |title=Tracking down Seattle's missing vintage streetcars |accessdate=June 9, 2009}}</ref> The remaining three cars were sold by King County to [[St. Louis]], for use on their planned heritage [[Delmar Loop Trolley]],<ref name=\"king-2016jan\"/><ref name=\"king-2016jun\">{{cite web |last1=Green |first1=Josh |title=Three iconic Seattle waterfront streetcars head to Midwest |url=http://www.king5.com/news/local/farewell-to-some-of-seattles-iconic-waterfront-streetcars/226941592 |publisher=[[KING-TV]] |accessdate=2016-08-10 |date=June 1, 2016}}</ref> for which they will need several modifications before they can be used;<ref name=\"taut-2016may\">{{cite news |title=Worldwide Review [regular news section] |magazine=[[Tramways & Urban Transit]] |publisher=Light Rail Transit Association |date=May 2016 |location=UK |page=193}}</ref> only one car is being retrofitted (by [[Gomaco Trolley Company|Gomaco]]) for service in St. Louis initially.<ref name=\"taut-2016aug-p312\">{{cite news |title=Worldwide Review [regular news section] |magazine=Tramways & Urban Transit |publisher=Light Rail Transit Association |date=August 2016 |location=UK |page=312}}</ref> The specific cars sold to St. Louis were Nos. 482, 512, and 518,<ref name=\"taut-2016aug-p312\"/> and they left Seattle in early June 2016.<ref name=\"king-2016jun\"/>  The streetcars retained by King County Metro are Nos. 272 and 605 (along with 525, which never entered service, and has been kept only as a source of parts).<ref name=\"taut-2016aug-p284\">{{cite news |title=Seattle accelerates its light rail plans |magazine=Tramways & Urban Transit |publisher=Light Rail Transit Association |date=August 2016 |location=UK |page=284}}</ref>  Because the warehouse in which they had been stored since the end of Waterfront Streetcar service in 2005 was due to be torn down, to make way for expansion of a Metro bus garage, the streetcars were moved out in early June 2016, to a private site in [[Arlington, Washington]], where they will be stored indefinitely, awaiting possible future developments in the proposals for their return to service.<ref name=\"taut-2016aug-p284\"/>\n\n==Route==\n\nThe line began at the Broad Street maintenance barn and mostly ran along the east side of Alaskan Way on [[Burlington Northern and Santa Fe Railway]] trackage under the [[Alaskan Way Viaduct]]. Its southernmost section in [[Pioneer Square, Seattle, Washington|Pioneer Square]] consisted of an east\u2013west track on South Main Street that passed Occidental Square and turned south onto 5th Avenue South. It terminated at South Jackson Street, across the street from [[International District/Chinatown station|International District station]] in the [[Downtown Seattle Transit Tunnel]].\n\n===Stations===\n\nAll of the stations (with the exception of the Occidental Park and Jackson Street stations) along the Alaskan Way were originally painted brown when the line first opened. In 2004, all of these stations were refurbished and repainted in Marine Blue.<ref>{{cite press release |date=August 11, 2003 |title=Metro goes retro with streetcar stations |url=http://transit.metrokc.gov/up/archives/2003/8-11wscstations.html |publisher=King County Metro Transit |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090814092357/http://transit.metrokc.gov/up/archives/2003/8-11wscstations.html |archivedate=August 14, 2009 |accessdate=January 9, 2019}}</ref> The Occidental and Jackson stations were designed to reflect the surrounding architecture along the streets when the line was extended in 1990. The Jackson Street stop featured an Asian Pagoda-style station while Occidental park had a vintage-style station.\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align:center\"\n|-\n! Name\n! Neighborhood\n! Location\n! Status\n! Other\n|-\n! colspan=6 style=\"background:green; color:yellow\" | Waterfront Streetcar\n|-\n| Broad Street\n| [[Central Waterfront, Seattle|Central Waterfront]]\n| Broad Street and Alaskan Way\n| Demolished in 2005\n| Served [[Myrtle Edwards Park]], [[Seattle Center]]. \n|-\n| Vine Street\n| [[Central Waterfront, Seattle|Central Waterfront]]\n| Vine Street and Alaskan Way\n| Demolished {{circa}} 2012\u201315\n| Served [[Port of Seattle]] headquarters, [[Victoria Clipper]], [[The Edgewater (Seattle, Washington)|The Edgewater]], [[The Art Institute of Seattle]]\n|-\n| Bell Street\n| [[Central Waterfront, Seattle|Central Waterfront]]\n| Bell Street and Alaskan Way\n| Demolished in 2018<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.portseattle.org/projects/alaskan-way-improvements-bell-harbor-cruise-terminal |title=Alaskan Way Improvements at Bell Harbor Cruise Terminal  |publisher=Port of Seattle |access-date=January 10, 2019}}</ref>\n| Served [[Belltown, Seattle, Washington|Belltown]], [[Central Waterfront, Seattle, Washington#Bell Street Pier.2C the Edgewater and Port Headquarters|Bell Street Pier]]\n|-\n| Pike Street\n| [[Central Waterfront, Seattle|Central Waterfront]]\n| Pike Street and Alaskan Way\n| Demolished in 2011\n| Served [[Seattle Aquarium]], Pike Hillclimb, [[Pike Place Market]]\n|-\n| University Street\n| [[Central Waterfront, Seattle|Central Waterfront]]\n| University Street and Alaskan Way\n| Demolished in 2011\n| Served [[Waterfront Park (Seattle)|Waterfront Park]], Bay Pavilion, Harbor Steps, [[Seattle Art Museum]], [[Downtown, Seattle, Washington|Downtown]]\n|-\n| Madison Street\n| [[Central Waterfront, Seattle|Central Waterfront]]\n| Madison Street and Alaskan Way\n| Demolished in 2011\n| Connections to [[Washington State Ferries]] [[Colman Dock]] ([[Bainbridge Island, Washington|Bainbridge Island]], [[Bremerton, Washington|Bremerton]])\n|-\n| Washington Street\n| [[Central Waterfront, Seattle|Central Waterfront]]\n| Washington Street and Alaskan Way\n| Demolished in 2011\n| Connection to [[Vashon, Washington|Vashon Island]] Passenger Ferry, [[West Seattle Water Taxi]]. Served [[Pioneer Square, Seattle, Washington|Pioneer Square]], [[Central Waterfront, Seattle, Washington#Harbor Entrance Pergola|Harbor Entrance Pergola]]\n|-\n| [[Occidental Park (Seattle)|Occidental Park]]\n| [[Pioneer Square, Seattle, Washington|Pioneer Square]]\n| S. Main Street and Occidental Avenue S.\n| Standing\n| Served [[Pioneer Square, Seattle, Washington|Pioneer Square]], [[Klondike Gold Rush National Historical Park]]\n|-\n| Jackson Street\n| [[International District, Seattle, Washington|International District]]\n| S. Jackson Street and Fifth Avenue S.\n| Demolished in 2019<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.soundtransit.org/st_sharepoint/download/sites/PRDA/FinalRecords/Resolution%20R2018-35.pdf |title=Budget Transfer for the Downtown Seattle and Regional Mobility Improvements Project |date=September 27, 2018 |publisher=Sound Transit |access-date=January 10, 2019}}</ref>\n| Connections to [[Downtown Seattle Transit Tunnel]] and [[King Street Station]]. Served [[Qwest Field]], [[Safeco Field]], [[Uwajimaya]]\n|}\n\n==Service and operations==\n\nPrior to its discontinuation in 2005, the Waterfront Streetcar line ran at a frequency of 20&nbsp;minutes from 6:30&nbsp;a.m. to 11:30&nbsp;p.m. on weekdays, and 10:00&nbsp;a.m. to 7:00&nbsp;p.m. on weekends.<ref>{{cite news |last=Eskenazi |first=Stuart |date=March 12, 2005 |title=No one wants to be villain in deciding streetcar's fate |page=A1 |url=https://www.seattletimes.com/seattle-news/no-one-wants-to-be-villain-in-deciding-streetcars-fate/ |work=The Seattle Times |accessdate=March 10, 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"MetroInfo\">{{cite web |title=George Benson Waterfront Streetcar Line: Metro Route 99 |url=http://transit.metrokc.gov/tops/bus/waterfront_streetcar.html |publisher=King County Metro |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20050719233218/http://transit.metrokc.gov/tops/bus/waterfront_streetcar.html |archivedate=July 19, 2005 |accessdate=March 10, 2020}}</ref> The streetcar was located entirely within Metro's Free Ride Area, but charged a normal fare paid with cash or a valid bus transfer or pass.<ref name=\"MetroInfo\"/>\n\nThe fleet of streetcar vehicles had wooden bench seating for 43 passengers and standing room for 40. The high platforms at stations allowed for level boarding, and the vehicles had room for wheelchairs and other mobility devices.<ref name=\"MetroInfo\"/> The streetcar line was labeled as Route 99, which also applied to its replacement bus route.<ref name=\"MetroInfo\"/> In 2004, its final year of full operations, the streetcar line carried 403,600 passengers.<ref>{{cite web |date=March 18, 2005 |title=Transit Ridership Report, Fourth Quarter 2004 |page=5 |url=https://www.apta.com/wp-content/uploads/Resources/resources/statistics/Documents/Ridership/2004_q4_ridership_APTA.pdf |publisher=[[American Public Transportation Association]] |accessdate=March 10, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n* [[Seattle Streetcar Network]]\n* [[South Lake Union Streetcar]]\n* [[First Hill Streetcar]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n===Additional sources===\n*{{cite web |title=Waterfront Streetcar gets a new home |work=King County Metro |url=http://transit.metrokc.gov/tops/bus/wsc_newhome.html |accessdate=December 23, 2005 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20060613003325/http://transit.metrokc.gov/tops/bus/wsc_newhome.html |archivedate=June 13, 2006 |url-status=dead |df=mdy}}\n*[http://www.historylink.org/essays/output.cfm?file_id=7121 Benson, George (1919-2004), Father of the Seattle Waterfront Streetcar]\n\n==External links==\n* {{commons category-inline|Waterfront Streetcar}}\n\n{{Puget Sound Transit}}\n\n[[Category:Transportation in Seattle]]\n[[Category:Heritage streetcar systems]]\n[[Category:Streetcars in Washington (state)]]\n[[Category:Railway lines opened in 1982]]\n[[Category:Railway lines closed in 2005]]\n[[Category:1982 establishments in Washington (state)]]\n[[Category:2005 disestablishments in Washington (state)]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Former heritage streetcar line in Seattle, Washington}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=January 2016}}\n{{Infobox rail line\n| name        = Waterfront Streetcar\n| color       = 002C59\n| logo        =\n| logo_width  =\n| image       = SeaWaterfrontStreetcar OccidentalPark.jpg\n| image_width =\n| caption     = Car 272 eastbound on Main Street,<br /> at the Occidental Park stop\n| type        = [[Heritage streetcar|Heritage]] [[Tram|streetcar]]\n| system      =\n| status      = Discontinued\n| locale      = [[Seattle, Washington|Seattle]]\n| start       = Broad Street at Alaskan Way\n| end         = Jackson Street at 5th Avenue\n| stations    = 9\n| routes      = 1\n| daily_ridership =\n| open        = May 29, 1982\n| close       = November 18, 2005\n| owner       =\n| operator    = [[King County Metro]]\n| character   = [[At-grade]]\n| depot       =\n| stock       = 5 [[W-class Melbourne tram|Melbourne W2 trams]]\n| linelength  = {{convert|1.6|mi|km|2|abbr=on}}\n| tracklength =\n| tracks      = \n| gauge       = {{RailGauge|ussg|allk=on}}\n| minradius   =\n| electrification = [[Overhead lines|Overhead wires]], 600 [[Volt|V]] [[Direct current|DC]]\n| speed       =\n| map         = {{infobox rdt|Seattle Waterfront Streetcar}}\n| map_state   =\n}}\n\nThe '''Waterfront Streetcar''', officially the '''George Benson Waterfront Streetcar Line''', was a [[heritage streetcar|heritage]] [[tram|streetcar line]] run by [[King County Metro]] in [[Seattle]], Washington, United States. It traveled for {{convert|1.6|mi|km|adj=on}} along [[Alaskan Way]] on the city's waterfront facing [[Elliott Bay]], under the [[Alaskan Way Viaduct]]. The Waterfront Streetcar used a fleet of five [[W-class Melbourne tram|W2 trams]] from [[Melbourne]], Australia.\n\nService began on May 29, 1982, the first streetcars to run in Seattle since the closure of the [[Seattle Municipal Street Railway]] on April 13, 1941. It initially terminated at [[Occidental Park (Seattle)|Occidental Park]] in [[Pioneer Square, Seattle|Pioneer Square]] until the line was extended to [[International District/Chinatown station]] in 1990. Service was officially suspended on November 18, 2005, when the maintenance barn and Broad Street station were demolished to make room for the [[Seattle Art Museum]]'s [[Olympic Sculpture Park]]. A large portion of the trackage and four stations were demolished in 2012 as part of the reconstruction of Alaskan Way.\n\nStreetcar service was replaced by King County Metro Route 99, which operated along Alaskan Way until February 2011 when construction forced Metro to reroute the line to 1st Avenue. King County Metro announced in January 2016 that a private venture would launch a fundraising effort to retrofit two of the historic Waterfront Streetcar vehicles to run alongside modern [[Seattle Streetcar]] vehicles on the [[Seattle Streetcar#Center City Connector|Center City Connector]] along 1st Avenue.\n\n==History==\n\nThe original [[Seattle Municipal Street Railway|city streetcar system]] in Seattle ceased operations in April 1941 and was replaced with a network of [[Trolleybuses in Seattle|electric trolleybuses]] and motor buses. City councilman [[George Benson (American politician)|George Benson]] (1919\u20132004) first proposed the idea of building a streetcar line along the Seattle waterfront in 1974, a year after he was elected to the council, to be operational in time for the national [[United States Bicentennial|Bicentennial]] on July 4, 1976.<ref name=\"times-1982may30\">{{cite news |last=Emery |first=Julie |title=Streetcar desire turns to real thing on waterfront |newspaper=The Seattle Times |date=May 30, 1982 |page=B1}}</ref><ref name=\"MT-1982Jan\">{{cite news |last=Price |first=J.H. |title=Museum News |magazine=[[Modern Tramway]] |publisher=[[Ian Allan Publishing]] |date=January 1982 |location=UK |page=30}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=Lane |first=Bob |date=August 20, 1974 |title=Firm will study streetcar plan |page=B8 |work=The Seattle Times}}</ref> The line would use vintage streetcars, and the goal was to create an attraction that would bring tourists and local residents to the waterfront, to help rejuvenate the area, which had already begun a slow transition from a purely industrial district to one with shops and cultural attractions such as the (then-planned, later built) [[Seattle Aquarium]]. Eventually, the proposal garnered enough support from the public and Benson's fellow council members that funds were allocated for an engineering and design study,<ref name=\"MT-1982Jan\"/> ultimately leading to the approval of the project.\n\nThe line used previously existing freight railroad tracks adjacent to [[Alaskan Way]], and construction for the streetcar project involved adding [[trolley wires|overhead trolley wires]], high-platform stations, and a [[passing loop|passing track]] near the middle of the line, which otherwise was [[Single-track railway|single-track]].<ref name=\"MT-1982Jan\"/>  The line started just north of Broad Street, near Pier 70, and until 1990 ran only as far south as Main Street, terminating at a station next to Alaskan Way, immediately south of Main.<ref name=\"MT-1982Jan\"/>\n\nService began on May 29, 1982,<ref name=\"times-1982may30\"/> which was the first streetcar run in Seattle since April 13, 1941. The first three streetcars had been brought to Seattle from [[Melbourne]], Australia, by Councilman Benson in 1978. They had been [[Melbourne and Metropolitan Tramways Board]] cars 482, 512 and 518, and they kept those numbers in Seattle. Two more Melbourne streetcars were acquired between 1990 and 1993. All were [[W-class Melbourne tram|W2-class]] trams that had originally been built between 1925 and 1930.\n\nIn 1989, construction began on a quarter-mile extension of the streetcar along Main Street and 5th Avenue to Jackson Street, to connect to the [[International District/Chinatown (Link station)|International District/Chinatown Station]] of the then-new [[Downtown Seattle Transit Tunnel]].<ref name=\"idea to reality\">{{cite news |last=Benson |first=George |url=http://www.historylink.org/index.cfm?DisplayPage=output.cfm&file_id=7271 |year=1992 |publisher=[[HistoryLink.org]] |title=The Seattle Waterfront Streetcar -- The Steep Grade from Idea to Reality by George Benson |accessdate=June 8, 2009}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=Carter |first=Don |date=July 26, 1989 |title=Ground broken for extension of the waterfront's streetcar line |page=B1 |work=Seattle Post-Intelligencer}}</ref> The extension opened for regular service on June 23, 1990.<ref name=\"idea to reality\"/><ref name=mt-sep90>''[[Tramways & Urban Transit|Modern Tramway]]'', September 1990, p. 321. [[Ian Allan Publishing]]/[[Light Rail Transit Association]] (UK).</ref> The line's fourth ex-Melbourne streetcar, No. 272, entered service earlier that month.<ref name=mt-sep90/> A fifth car of the same type, No. 605, entered service on June 1, 1993.<ref name=\"LRMT-1993Sep\">{{cite news |title=World News [regular news section] |magazine=[[Light Rail & Modern Tramway]] |publisher=[[Ian Allan Publishing]] |date=September 1993 |location=UK |page=249}}</ref> On June 1, 2020, the King County Council approved legislation to rename the line in honor of councilmember Benson, christening it the \"George Benson Waterfront Streetcar Line\". The streetcar stations were rebranded and repainted in August 2003.<ref>{{cite press release |date=August 11, 2003 |title=Metro goes retro with streetcar stations |url=http://transit.metrokc.gov/up/archives/2003/8-11wscstations.html |publisher=King County Metro |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090814092357/http://transit.metrokc.gov/up/archives/2003/8-11wscstations.html |archivedate=August 14, 2009 |accessdate=March 10, 2020}}</ref>\n\n===Cancellation of service===\n\n[[File:Seattle streetcar at Broad Street Station.jpg|thumb|left|Broad Street station]]\nThe streetcar ceased operation on November 18, 2005, when the maintenance barn was demolished to make room for the [[Seattle Art Museum]]'s [[Olympic Sculpture Park]].<ref name=\"lastday\">{{cite news |date=November 19, 2005 |title=Waterfront trolley's last lullaby until 2007 |work=[[Seattle Post-Intelligencer]] |url=http://www.seattlepi.com/transportation/249090_streetcar19.html |accessdate=May 3, 2010}}{{dead link|date=August 2011}}</ref> A new maintenance barn was proposed to be built at Occidental Park to allow the resumption of operations as early as summer 2007.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://community.seattletimes.nwsource.com/archive/?date=20060629&slug=trolleybarn29m |title=Trolley-maintenance barn plan on hold; streetcar future unclear |work=The Seattle Times |date=June 29, 2006 |accessdate=August 6, 2011}}</ref> However, [[King County Metro|Metro]] cancelled involvement after delays made the new facility unlikely to be completed before the demolition of the [[Alaskan Way Viaduct]] began.<ref name=sea-times-2008apr>{{cite news |last=Eskenazi |first=Stuart |url=http://seattletimes.nwsource.com/html/localnews/2004341603_streetcar11m.html |date=April 11, 2008 |newspaper=[[The Seattle Times]] |title=Waterfront streetcar: Is it gone for good? |accessdate=June 8, 2009}}</ref> An alternative proposal by the [[Port of Seattle]] was to extend the line northward along [[Myrtle Edwards Park]] to [[Smith Cove (Washington)|Smith Cove]], where a new maintenance barn would be built on Port property.<ref>{{cite news |last=Hadley |first=Jane |url=http://www.seattlepi.com/transportation/217355_samtrolley24.html |date=March 24, 2005 |newspaper=[[Seattle Post-Intelligencer]] |title=Port plan would extend and save waterfront trolley |accessdate=December 14, 2009}}</ref> This proposal was not pursued.\n\nIn 2007, two years into the suspension of service, the route was named by National Geographic Society as one of the 10 Great Streetcar routes.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.thestar.com/News/GTA/article/289399 |first=Christopher |last=Hume |author2=Kalinowski, Tess |newspaper=[[Toronto Star]] |date=December 29, 2007 |title=Toronto streetcar named among world's best |accessdate=July 24, 2008}}</ref>\n\nIn spring 2012, a large portion of the trackage and the stations at Pike, University, Madison and Washington streets were demolished in as a part of the construction project drilling a [[Alaskan Way Viaduct replacement tunnel|deep bore tunnel]] to replace the Alaskan Way Viaduct.\n\nThe City of Seattle began studying the possibility of bringing streetcars back to the city center in late 2012. The locally preferred alternative for this project adopted in late 2014 supported a route along 1st Avenue and not Alaskan Way. James Corner Field Operations, the Manhattan-based landscape-architecture firm hired to recommend a new vision for the Seattle waterfront once the Viaduct has been demolished, also recommended the Streetcar not be returned to Alaskan Way, but to nearby First Avenue instead.\n\nWhile future plans for the line were determined, the streetcars were stored in an old warehouse in SoDo for more than a decade. In 2015, the Federal Transit Administration informed King County that if the streetcars are not put back in service soon, Metro would need to pay $205,000 to compensate the agency for its remaining investment in the cars.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web |url=http://saveourstreetcar.org/seattles-old-waterfront-streetcars-will-live-on-in-different-ways/ |title=Seattle's old waterfront streetcars will live on \u2013 in different ways [excerpt from KING 5 News story] |date=January 14, 2016|access-date = August 10, 2016 |website=Saveourstreetcar.org |publisher=Friends of the Benson Trolleys |last= |first=}}</ref> At the same time, the warehouse used to store the streetcars was in poor condition and the land needed for expansion of a neighboring bus base.<ref name=\":1\" />\n\n[[File:Ex-Melbourne tram 482 loaded onto truck trailer in Seattle for its move to St Louis, June 2016.jpg|thumb|left|Car 482 loaded onto a truck trailer, about to leave for St. Louis]]\n\nIn January 2016, it was announced that a private venture, Friends of the Benson Trolleys, was intending to raise the money required to retrofit two of the streetcars to allow them to be used on the future [[Seattle Streetcar#Future lines|Center City Connector]] on 1st Avenue.<ref name=\"king-2016jan\">{{cite news |last=Green |first=Josh |date=January 14, 2016 |title=Seattle's old waterfront streetcars will live on - in different ways |url=http://www.king5.com/story/news/local/seattle/2016/01/14/seattles-old-waterfront-streetcars-live---different-ways/78825108/ |publisher=[[KING-TV]] |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160125062226/http://www.king5.com/story/news/local/seattle/2016/01/14/seattles-old-waterfront-streetcars-live---different-ways/78825108/ |archivedate=January 25, 2016 |accessdate=January 14, 2016}}</ref> The plan closely mirrors one suggested in May 2009 by then Seattle Mayor, [[Greg Nickels]].<ref name=\"Seattle Post Globe\">{{cite news |last=Murakami |first=Kery |url=http://seattlepostglobe.org/2009/05/16/tracking-down-seattles-missing-vintage-streetcars |date=May 16, 2009 |publisher=[[Seattle PostGlobe]] |title=Tracking down Seattle's missing vintage streetcars |accessdate=June 9, 2009}}</ref> The remaining three cars were sold by King County to [[St. Louis]], for use on their planned heritage [[Delmar Loop Trolley]],<ref name=\"king-2016jan\"/><ref name=\"king-2016jun\">{{cite web |last1=Green |first1=Josh |title=Three iconic Seattle waterfront streetcars head to Midwest |url=http://www.king5.com/news/local/farewell-to-some-of-seattles-iconic-waterfront-streetcars/226941592 |publisher=[[KING-TV]] |accessdate=2016-08-10 |date=June 1, 2016}}</ref> for which they will need several modifications before they can be used;<ref name=\"taut-2016may\">{{cite news |title=Worldwide Review [regular news section] |magazine=[[Tramways & Urban Transit]] |publisher=Light Rail Transit Association |date=May 2016 |location=UK |page=193}}</ref> only one car is being retrofitted (by [[Gomaco Trolley Company|Gomaco]]) for service in St. Louis initially.<ref name=\"taut-2016aug-p312\">{{cite news |title=Worldwide Review [regular news section] |magazine=Tramways & Urban Transit |publisher=Light Rail Transit Association |date=August 2016 |location=UK |page=312}}</ref> The specific cars sold to St. Louis were Nos. 482, 512, and 518,<ref name=\"taut-2016aug-p312\"/> and they left Seattle in early June 2016.<ref name=\"king-2016jun\"/>  The streetcars retained by King County Metro are Nos. 272 and 605 (along with 525, which never entered service, and has been kept only as a source of parts).<ref name=\"taut-2016aug-p284\">{{cite news |title=Seattle accelerates its light rail plans |magazine=Tramways & Urban Transit |publisher=Light Rail Transit Association |date=August 2016 |location=UK |page=284}}</ref>  Because the warehouse in which they had been stored since the end of Waterfront Streetcar service in 2005 was due to be torn down, to make way for expansion of a Metro bus garage, the streetcars were moved out in early June 2016, to a private site in [[Arlington, Washington]], where they will be stored indefinitely, awaiting possible future developments in the proposals for their return to service.<ref name=\"taut-2016aug-p284\"/>\n\n==Route==\n\nThe line began at the Broad Street maintenance barn and mostly ran along the east side of Alaskan Way on [[Burlington Northern and Santa Fe Railway]] trackage under the [[Alaskan Way Viaduct]]. Its southernmost section in [[Pioneer Square, Seattle, Washington|Pioneer Square]] consisted of an east\u2013west track on South Main Street that passed Occidental Square and turned south onto 5th Avenue South. It terminated at South Jackson Street, across the street from [[International District/Chinatown station|International District station]] in the [[Downtown Seattle Transit Tunnel]].\n\n===Stations===\n\nAll of the stations (with the exception of the Occidental Park and Jackson Street stations) along the Alaskan Way were originally painted brown when the line first opened. In 2004, all of these stations were refurbished and repainted in Marine Blue.<ref>{{cite press release |date=August 11, 2003 |title=Metro goes retro with streetcar stations |url=http://transit.metrokc.gov/up/archives/2003/8-11wscstations.html |publisher=King County Metro Transit |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090814092357/http://transit.metrokc.gov/up/archives/2003/8-11wscstations.html |archivedate=August 14, 2009 |accessdate=January 9, 2019}}</ref> The Occidental and Jackson stations were designed to reflect the surrounding architecture along the streets when the line was extended in 1990. The Jackson Street stop featured an Asian Pagoda-style station while Occidental park had a vintage-style station.\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align:center\"\n|-\n! Name\n! Neighborhood\n! Location\n! Status\n! Other\n|-\n! colspan=6 style=\"background:green; color:yellow\" | Waterfront Streetcar\n|-\n| Broad Street\n| [[Central Waterfront, Seattle|Central Waterfront]]\n| Broad Street and Alaskan Way\n| Demolished in 2005\n| Served [[Myrtle Edwards Park]], [[Seattle Center]]. \n|-\n| Vine Street\n| [[Central Waterfront, Seattle|Central Waterfront]]\n| Vine Street and Alaskan Way\n| Demolished {{circa}} 2012\u201315\n| Served [[Port of Seattle]] headquarters, [[Victoria Clipper]], [[The Edgewater (Seattle, Washington)|The Edgewater]], [[The Art Institute of Seattle]]\n|-\n| Bell Street\n| [[Central Waterfront, Seattle|Central Waterfront]]\n| Bell Street and Alaskan Way\n| Demolished in 2018<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.portseattle.org/projects/alaskan-way-improvements-bell-harbor-cruise-terminal |title=Alaskan Way Improvements at Bell Harbor Cruise Terminal  |publisher=Port of Seattle |access-date=January 10, 2019}}</ref>\n| Served [[Belltown, Seattle, Washington|Belltown]], [[Central Waterfront, Seattle, Washington#Bell Street Pier.2C the Edgewater and Port Headquarters|Bell Street Pier]]\n|-\n| Pike Street\n| [[Central Waterfront, Seattle|Central Waterfront]]\n| Pike Street and Alaskan Way\n| Demolished in 2011\n| Served [[Seattle Aquarium]], Pike Hillclimb, [[Pike Place Market]]\n|-\n| University Street\n| [[Central Waterfront, Seattle|Central Waterfront]]\n| University Street and Alaskan Way\n| Demolished in 2011\n| Served [[Waterfront Park (Seattle)|Waterfront Park]], Bay Pavilion, Harbor Steps, [[Seattle Art Museum]], [[Downtown, Seattle, Washington|Downtown]]\n|-\n| Madison Street\n| [[Central Waterfront, Seattle|Central Waterfront]]\n| Madison Street and Alaskan Way\n| Demolished in 2011\n| Connections to [[Washington State Ferries]] [[Colman Dock]] ([[Bainbridge Island, Washington|Bainbridge Island]], [[Bremerton, Washington|Bremerton]])\n|-\n| Washington Street\n| [[Central Waterfront, Seattle|Central Waterfront]]\n| Washington Street and Alaskan Way\n| Demolished in 2011\n| Connection to [[Vashon, Washington|Vashon Island]] Passenger Ferry, [[West Seattle Water Taxi]]. Served [[Pioneer Square, Seattle, Washington|Pioneer Square]], [[Central Waterfront, Seattle, Washington#Harbor Entrance Pergola|Harbor Entrance Pergola]]\n|-\n| [[Occidental Park (Seattle)|Occidental Park]]\n| [[Pioneer Square, Seattle, Washington|Pioneer Square]]\n| S. Main Street and Occidental Avenue S.\n| Standing\n| Served [[Pioneer Square, Seattle, Washington|Pioneer Square]], [[Klondike Gold Rush National Historical Park]]\n|-\n| Jackson Street\n| [[International District, Seattle, Washington|International District]]\n| S. Jackson Street and Fifth Avenue S.\n| Demolished in 2019<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.soundtransit.org/st_sharepoint/download/sites/PRDA/FinalRecords/Resolution%20R2018-35.pdf |title=Budget Transfer for the Downtown Seattle and Regional Mobility Improvements Project |date=September 27, 2018 |publisher=Sound Transit |access-date=January 10, 2019}}</ref>\n| Connections to [[Downtown Seattle Transit Tunnel]] and [[King Street Station]]. Served [[Qwest Field]], [[Safeco Field]], [[Uwajimaya]]\n|}\n\n==Service and operations==\n\nPrior to its discontinuation in 2005, the Waterfront Streetcar line ran at a frequency of 20&nbsp;minutes from 6:30&nbsp;a.m. to 11:30&nbsp;p.m. on weekdays, and 10:00&nbsp;a.m. to 7:00&nbsp;p.m. on weekends.<ref>{{cite news |last=Eskenazi |first=Stuart |date=March 12, 2005 |title=No one wants to be villain in deciding streetcar's fate |page=A1 |url=https://www.seattletimes.com/seattle-news/no-one-wants-to-be-villain-in-deciding-streetcars-fate/ |work=The Seattle Times |accessdate=March 10, 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"MetroInfo\">{{cite web |title=George Benson Waterfront Streetcar Line: Metro Route 99 |url=http://transit.metrokc.gov/tops/bus/waterfront_streetcar.html |publisher=King County Metro |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20050719233218/http://transit.metrokc.gov/tops/bus/waterfront_streetcar.html |archivedate=July 19, 2005 |accessdate=March 10, 2020}}</ref> The streetcar was located entirely within Metro's Free Ride Area, but charged a normal fare paid with cash or a valid bus transfer or pass.<ref name=\"MetroInfo\"/>\n\nThe fleet of streetcar vehicles had wooden bench seating for 43 passengers and standing room for 40. The high platforms at stations allowed for level boarding, and the vehicles had room for wheelchairs and other mobility devices.<ref name=\"MetroInfo\"/> The streetcar line was labeled as Route 99, which also applied to its replacement bus route.<ref name=\"MetroInfo\"/> In 2004, its final year of full operations, the streetcar line carried 403,600 passengers.<ref>{{cite web |date=March 18, 2005 |title=Transit Ridership Report, Fourth Quarter 2004 |page=5 |url=https://www.apta.com/wp-content/uploads/Resources/resources/statistics/Documents/Ridership/2004_q4_ridership_APTA.pdf |publisher=[[American Public Transportation Association]] |accessdate=March 10, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n* [[Seattle Streetcar Network]]\n* [[South Lake Union Streetcar]]\n* [[First Hill Streetcar]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n===Additional sources===\n*{{cite web |title=Waterfront Streetcar gets a new home |work=King County Metro |url=http://transit.metrokc.gov/tops/bus/wsc_newhome.html |accessdate=December 23, 2005 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20060613003325/http://transit.metrokc.gov/tops/bus/wsc_newhome.html |archivedate=June 13, 2006 |url-status=dead |df=mdy}}\n*[http://www.historylink.org/essays/output.cfm?file_id=7121 Benson, George (1919-2004), Father of the Seattle Waterfront Streetcar]\n\n==External links==\n* {{commons category-inline|Waterfront Streetcar}}\n\n{{Puget Sound Transit}}\n\n[[Category:Transportation in Seattle]]\n[[Category:Heritage streetcar systems]]\n[[Category:Streetcars i